text: This account will not be used any more to post short messages from our round the world trip. Instead see: http://trip20092010.blogspot.com/
Ferihegy. Free wireless here! Flying to Prague, then Tallinn. Flight delayed from 8.20 to 9.30.
Ataturk Airport. Flight here bumpy, food good. Movie: Ice Age 3. Now been sleeping. Next flight at 11.50.
Eger. Back in Europe. Celebrating with palinka.
Airport bus. Leaving Africa after 3 months here. Next stop Joburg, then Istanbul, then Budapest.
The Backpack. Back from a 5h/13km hike over the Table Mountain to the Kirstenbosch botanical gardens. Robben Island booked out.
The Backpack. Raining. Going to visit the townships today. Later Robben Island, unless it is cancelled due to rain/wind.
The Backpack. Going to karaoke on Lang Str. Rainy/sleepy day today. Visited Langa and Khayelitsha in the morning. Robben Island cancelled.
The Backpack. Today visited the African Penguins, the Topstones gemstone factory, the Cape of Good Hope, and the Steenberg wine tasting.
Hostel Backpack. Nice twin room. Day too windy for Leeukop hike, so explored the downtown again.
The Game Restaurant, Cape Town. Eating an eland. 73-days with Absolute Africa have ended.
Stellenbosch. Exploring the town. There is supposed to be a university somewhere. Do they have a CL department? Others wine-touring.
Fiddlers Creek. On the RSA side of the Orange river, where we swam. No crocodiles. Today drive day.
Solitaire. Lunchbreak. No rainfall here since March. Crossed the t. of Capricorn earlier.
Sesriem. Visited the sand dunes and vleis with dead trees. Dali-like landscapes. Guide demonstrated click language (San).
Swakopmund. Standup sandboarding felt almost like snowboarding. No skilift though. Reached 69 km/h on the lie-down board. Day's best was 74.
Otherwise eating Italian and German food, going to museums and cinemas. This evening might go to Mondesa and D.R.C. (nearby townships).
Tomorrow leaving Swakopmund and heading south: Sesriem, Fish River Canyon.
Swakopmund. Chilly German town between the desert and the ocean. Stay here for 4 nights. Tomorrow go sandboarding.
Previous highlights: petting cheetahs (at Cheetah Park), Himba village, Brandberg rock paintings, Cape Cross seal colony.
Okasomething. Computers/internet is slow, stores have no sour cream. Saw a bare-breasted woman at OK Foods.
Got back from the Etosha NP. Lots of waterholes. The usual animals visiting them. Occasional lions and rhinos. The springbocks springing.
Maun. Back from a 3 day/2 night Mokoro safari in the Okavango Delta. Real bushcamp. No aardvark, just its holes. Tomorrow enter Namibia.
Livingstone. Jogged to the falls (11.6km), baboon stole our vanilla biscuits (2000 ZK), watched rafters and bungee jumpers from the bridge.
Then took a local bus back to Livingstone. While the bus was filling up (they leave only when full), discussed SISU with the driver.
SISU is a Finnish word which the driver knew, strangely. (We always introduce ourselves as coming from Finland, to keep things simpler.)
Then a quick swim in the pool, and then "Harry Potter" in "Capitol" (10,000 pp), were the only ones there. No dubbing, subtitles in Chinese.
Livingstone. Slow day. Swam a lot in the pool. Lunch: instant noodles + canned tuna. Visited Zimbabwean black market: bag of vodka: 1 USD.
Livingstone. Spending 5 nights here. Yesterday at the Victoria Falls. Swam in the Devil's Pool and then in the Angel's Armchair.
Optional activities in Livingstone are expensive and/or dangerous: bungee jumping (110m), rafting, gorge swing, etc.
Will go and watch the latest Harry Potter movie instead, or just relax by the pool at the camp (Grubby's Grotto).
Mazabuka. On the way to Lake Kariba and its houseboats. Spent two days in the South Luangwa park: saw the leopard, completing the big 5.
Lilongwe. Shopping for food at Shoprite for today and the next 3 days. Spent more than an hour on this which leaves just 30min for internet.
Now going to the border (of Malawi-Zambia), i.e. will have no time to  see the center of Lilongwe. Maybe there is nothing there anyway?
Lilongwe. Spent the last 3 nights on Kande beach and got to know the local village. The locals suck in singing, dancing, fishing, and bao.
The locals are excellent woodcarvers though: our bus is now filled with Malawi chairs, tables, keyrings, bao boards, hair pins, boxes, etc.
Tomorrow will enter Zambia for more game drives, lake Kariba houseboats, and Victoria Falls.
Chitimba camp, Lake Malawi. Entry to Malawi without problems, only the borderguard wanted to register me as from "Estonia (Hungary)". Weird.
The local beer Kuche Kuche costs 200 Kwacha, internet (wireless but slow): 15 Kwacha per minute.
Lake Malawi is nice. Would like to swim in it after a sweaty day in the truck, but afraid of bilharzia.
Dar. Back from Zanzibar. The highlight was Forodhani night market. Had Zanzibari pizza and octopus with chips. Tomorrow leaving for Malawi.
Sunset Bungalows, Kendwa, Zanzibar. Yesterday snorkeled, got sunburned. Today Jozani forest: saw red colobus monkeys. Also fed sea turtles.
Dar. Leaving in 1h for Zanzibar. Stayed 2 nights at Kunduchi House on the beach. Yesterday took a City Bus to Dar and saw the fish market.
Dar on igav linn. Lootsin leida rohkem multikultuursust, nt india templeid, aga on ainult mosheed ja aafriklased. Kalaturg oli huvitav.
Coming up:1 night in Stone Town, 3 nights on the beach on the northern coast. Turns out Ramadan starts today. Impact for us unclear.
Masai Camp, Arusha. Yesterday at Ngorongoro. Saw a lion family eat a buffalo. Also cheetah, jackals, hyenas. No leopard though. :(
The Simba camp at Ngorongoro was right at the crater rim. Zebras and an elephan walked close by (10 meters) in the evening.
Today facing a long drive to Dar. The roads in Tanzania seem to be good though (except for the one between Namanga and Arusha, of course).
Arusha. Night at Snake Park. Decided to skip Serengeti. Too expensive: 245 USD. Visited Tengeru on dala-dala. 27 people on 15 seats!
Dala-dala is called "matatu" in Kenya. There the law limits the number of passengers to 14. See also http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Share_taxi
Today will spend another night at Snake Park. Tomorrow will go to Ngorongoro on 4x4, camp at the crater, and then gamedrive in the morning.
See also http://bit.ly/14c9aY
The Meserani Snake Park campsite is very popular with overlanders. Yesterday some 7-8 trucks camped there. http://www.meseranisnakepark.com/

Today at Giraffe Centre (http://bit.ly/Zs9nx
 and an elephant orphanage (http://www.sheldrickwildlifetrust.org/).
Tomorrow facing the 7-hour drive to Arusha, Tanzania on the horribly bumpy road. This will be the 3rd time for us on this road.
(For some reason the SMSs do not go through, either Zain or Twitter must have a problem.)
Back in Nairobi. Yesterday afternoon and today morning at Masai Mara. Saw many lions, hippos, and a cheetah's failed attempt to get a zebra.
Nakuru again. Next stop lake Naivasha. Will spend two nights there, visiting the Hell's gate national park.
Lake Nakuru national park gate. Lake pink with flamingos. Saw a gray blob. Rhino? Gamedrive starting now.
Entebbe. Sleepy ex-capital of Uganda. Heavy rain in the morning. Our first real rain in Africa. Cooked breakfest in the rain. Tent is wet.
Yesterday at the equator again. People there agreed with my GPS: the real equator is 10m south. Their "water demonsatration" still worked.
See also http://bit.ly/pXILn
Long form trip notes are available at https://dl.getdropbox.com/u/1397729/trip2009/index.html. This website is updated irregularly.
Still Ruhengeri. Slow day today, but in the evening visited a Twa (Pygmy) village. Took pictures of the children and the villagers dancing.
Visited Guhonda and his family (Sabyinyo). Found them after a short walk over the (Irish) potato fields and through a bamboo forest.
Guhonda mildly attacked our guide Francois who went too close (3m). They know each other for 29 years, so it was a nothing serious.
Read more about the Sabyinyo family e.g. at http://www.rwandaecotours.com/sabyinyo.html
Kabale. Last night in Mbarara. Today all day in the truck. Saw a crowned crane. Hope to reach Rwanda today. Tomorrow gorillas.
Hostel, Ruhengeri. Finally in Rwanda. Kabale-Kisoro-Cyanika road through hills. Some with bamboo forests, some cultivated. Road horrible.
Still at Nile River Explorer camp. Today went to Jinja by motorized boda-boda. Nice quiet town. Very many banks. Lunch by the lake/river.
Camp, Jinja. Visited some local schools, painted two classrooms in Butiki, dined with the teachers, donated 20 USD, and bought a T-shirt.
Read more about the Soft Power project at http://www.softpowereducation.com/
Camp/rafting center, Jinja. All day in the truck. Border crossing to Uganda without problems: passport + $50 is the only info that is asked.
Nakuru. Spent a chilly night at Thomson's Falls at 2360m. This morning visited an orphanage, played with ~20 kids and gave them stationery.
On the way to Nakuru had a nice view to the Rift Valley. Bought an alabaster plate with a map of the rift. Samahani hapana is not effective.
Nanyuki again. Was at an all female Samburu village, and at the Samburu Game Reserve: elephant, buffalo, duma, and lots of zebras/giraffes.
Nanyuki, close to Mt Kenya. Short internet and market break. On the way here crossed the equator.
Bantu lodge, 150km north of Nairobi. Only baboons and marabus on this 1st safari day. 21 people on the truck (Pumba).
Nairobi. Looking for a self-service laundry. Unsuccessful so far. The Heron (9990 KSh for 2p for 2n) has a nice lobby but the bed sucks.
Java House. Free but slow wireless. Eating burgers, drinking juice and tea. European prices. Search for self-service laundry failed.
Earlier at bookstore. Bought "The State of Africa" by Martin Meredith and a Swahili phrasebook. Considering buying a book about animals.
Btw, the pied crow (see 2009-07-17) turned out to be a white-naped raven.
Internet place in Arusha. Yesterday got back from Kili. Today going back to Nairobi, if the Riverside Shuttle shows up to pick us up.
Mweka hut 3076m. Early morning conquered Uhuru 5895m in 6h from Barafu! There before sunrise. Cold. Steep. Dull. In total 11h hiking today.
Barafu camp 4677m. Hiked 2.5h. Only alpine desert. Nice view to Mawenzi. Now lunch then rest then dinner then rest then to the summit at 00.
Karanga (peanut) camp 4020m. 3h hike up and down. Rough terraine, rock wall climbs, icy creeks. We are above clouds all the time.
Barranco camp 4 000m. Morning frosty, clear view to Meru. A pied crow stole our soap. Hiked 6.5h, incl a windy detour to Lava tower, 4650m.
Lunchbreak. 3730m, above the clouds. About 1h to Shira camp at 3800m.
Shira camp. Hiked up here in 5h. Explored the Shira cave, washed feet in warm water. Now expecting tea and popcorn soon. Windy.
Machame gate. Ready to go. Us 2 and 11 helpers, incl guide Msuri. Today 6-8h, to 3000m. Kwa heri.
Machame camp. Arrived in 4.5h. Had Milo and popcorn, now waiting for dinner. The sun has set, it's cold.
Arusha Post Office Internet corner. Earlier bought a map of Arusha and an English-Swahili phrasebook for 5000 TSh (4 USD).
Karibu, Nairobi. Visa easily. Airport empty, no other flights so early. Must wait 3h for shuttle to Arusha. Sleepy.
Namanga bordercrossing. Waiting for tanzanian visa. No wildbeest, no big 5, just lean goats and cows, masai men on bikes, red soil, top  ...
Dinner at Arusha Backpackers: sizzling vegi + Arushaburger:18k shillings. Walked along the main street, no white people, many solicitors.
Arushaban vagyunk,  voros, poros utakon ertunk ide. a vadallatoknak nyoma sincs. :( de mar lattunk a meru hegyet es a kilimandzsarot.
Nyyd magama. Umbes 24 tundi jarjest yleval olnud. Teekond Nairobi-Arusha oli kurnav, tolmune ja auklik tee, 7 tundi koos piiriyletusega.
Woke up, ate, ate the weekly pill of Mephaquin. Flying today to Cairo, then Nairobi. Flight leaves at 16:45 from Ferihegy. Almost packed.
Landed safely in cairo, now boarding for nairobi, taking off 22:45.
Going to tesco, stuck in traffic.
Signed up with Miles & More, as both EGYPTAIR and Turkish Airlines are in StarAlliance.
Woke up. Possibly will go to Bu"kksze'k to swim.
Testing m.twitter.com
1st day. Woke up at 10. Everything almost packed. Windy and cold in Tallinn. Will wear my Jacke and boots to the plane.
At Tallinn Lennart Meri International Airport. Flying Czech Air to Prague, then Budapest. Check-in luggage (i.e. the big backbag) was 13 kg.
Arrived in Eger.
Just signed up with Twitter...
Testing Twitux
